The Architecture of the Web: HTML
While Python manages the logic and memory of an application, HTML provides the structural semantics required to render content in a browser.
Often misunderstood as a programming language, HTML is a declarative markup language that uses a tree-like hierarchy known as the Document Object Model (DOM).
At its core, every HTML element is an instruction to the browser’s rendering engine, defining the "what" of a page—be it a heading, a container, 
or a hyperlinked reference—rather than the "how" of its appearance.
Modern HTML5 has evolved beyond simple text tagging into a robust framework that supports native multimedia embedding, canvas-based graphics,
and persistent client-side storage.
It acts as the essential bridge between raw data and user interface,
ensuring that information is not only visible but also accessible and SEO-optimized through meaningful tags.
