## 3. The "Glue": How Python and HTML Communicate
In a modern stack, Python and HTML are usually bridged by a **Web Framework** (like Django) or an **API**.

| Method | How it works |
| :--- | :--- |
| **Server-Side Rendering (SSR)** | Python code runs on the server, takes data from a database, and "injects" it into an HTML template before sending the final string to the browser. |
| **Client-Side Rendering (CSR)** | Python acts as a "Data Provider" (via an API). It sends raw data (JSON) to the browser, and JavaScript uses that data to build the HTML elements on the fly. |

---

### A Note on Performance
Because Python is **interpreted** and manages memory automatically, it is often slower than compiled languages.
However, because HTML is **declarative**, the browser's engine (written in C++) is highly optimized to render it.
This is why you can write complex logic in Python and still have a snappy user interface in HTML.
